as. 28 febu 1682
Eyan m Aillem Sealy
In the 18 uitt. ded answer yd of 28 past, sence recd. yd of P pr. by which you
express the quanthe of sloverseed, you onder by the sonn a ton wee reahon
op heads, which should farr epeced the formar order of 3 thous and or 2 thous and be
gett that com. beeng so much rises shall onely with much a do provide the liast
for as yett have not been able to gett any of the best new seed under 4 stivere, all
so that I feare, I shall be fored to give 4 sp for the old, I have abour 6o1
ready bought the least markett day, & as much as I see the old will cost you
one with an other vere neare 2 p so shall provide accordingley, itt is never
seen how that com is bought up, & itt will oblige mee to go nound by the boores
& buy what I can gett to yd prijses, for all what comes to markett is sold as sorne
as sett then the markett place of that com is 5 leages off, & I'll endeavour to
have the parcill compleated before next mankett day be past, or elces I might sean
more aesing, you may depend on my endeavour for yd advantidge as much of
for my doudre. I have witt to ostende & Rotterdam to know where the first
opportunitie is of shipping for yd part I shall do all I can to serve you to content
London mr. Bruny Colliun
Jusf when my last on the 25 curtt. was gon away, have recd. yo of 10d., tis good
I have bought no more mathers till I have yd punther opnitw, I have also contrrmanded
John Button to buy those 2 bales att Bulst, & have his answer, that he shall not meddle
with y. which perhaps you will finde also by the inclosed. the 2 I wrott you off at
ƒ37- have putt off, so that I am not obliged to take them oneles JB. had engaged his
word fuither thin I know. as for the deluge tis certains that never the like hashwed for
itt hath been genonall, & all the mather contrey as well as all other low ground is underwater
& that shill, t is trre some beleave & say that whien the wathers shall be out that the mathers
6d
will come to I fection, butt who can tell I confess every where are thes greatest endeavours don
of the wold to keep their grounds, yett the vers land, or polders whoes disches are not
broake, butt where the wathe did onely aun over, is still under water, & will not be ont yett
n & how shall itt be tossible to repare such discles, as are broake, & whene holes aved
fallen that an eastindia ship could saile through, & such are to many here abouts, butt how itt is
in dolland I cnow not, though I am sure tis badd enough. as for yd. resting goods I have
no occasion for them to take y upon my acctt. butt I'll sell them, whes I can, for they must
P.S beeng traged to recave the bales of mathers att ƒ 38.: 1o have
have their turne foreed to draw onyou £100- att 2p att 31.2 a 28 febo 168
Londen mr. Genry Maynard fo the ord. of m sac. Bonvers valew of hin ecould finde no liss to draw to please
to accept & raps to yd. acutt
mij last to you was on the corr. with a bill of £160- on m. Edmund warner att 35„ 2
for yd acctt inclosed £150- att sight on adam Grover for my acctt. for which please
to procure the need full, I hope to remitt you overy week to incorridge you as much, as
I can expect from you in the goods. now I have before mee yd of 6 & 13 curtt with
invoyce & patt. of 3 packes aboard steven warner sor mij ½ part in them shall give
you creditt, butt I finde you sende not goods to the pattarnes & discripsion I gave, in
the first you send lighter grayes then I demand, & non as browne as my brownist patt.
thereby already 7 grays where as in all I urott for 4 a 5, & yett nott one you send as browne
as I have desined so I must have one or 2 of the brownest that are to be had nept to
Must. the gold & blackes are to reddith, & that I told you to avoid, N. 360 is to light
& not one patt. of what I sent you comes neare itt, I hope the aest will better aggree
& to make our assortment the better, must have some browne cullours, aclording too the
inclosed patt., of which please to provide the needfull, as therem mentioned, & if you
can not finde the bleews as desined of about 5 sta yd lett them allone & make up this
bale whith some more ordinary or low prijses of the same cullours of the heys, & make
the bale of mocks up with the greens, ensseed of the blews, butt what sors of blews did
you sond formerly to the indos Bouwens of so low prijse. negleet nothing in the GW
silver marchs, for I must have them about caster. if m. Scawen bayes something
for mee att the eastindia sale, shall want 24 demy white cottens, so you may sick them
up, white you meet a penniworth, 12 demne & att least, of about 24 a 25 senee a good
as to the northren goods is loss to yd. menagement the better they be the better that
trade will take: I could with wee were once neare I K I assure you no cloth he
sends from Hull, butt proves 2„2½ & 3 y over measire: butt follow yd. way & intention
gett I doubt yd. bayes rappers att 44:6 will rott do, you must needs send for some out
of the north because wee ought not to bestow more then 40, or 41 ƒ forviappers, itt
matters not if they be of a counse wooll, if they be butt thich broad, & heary. asto
the cxrons they wil be noted to yd dircekon: neglect not do wnte off y of the prets
as for mr. Bondon & Garduer, their letters do finde due camplynd with thnckes to
you for yd raccomandation, yd. naigbbair Thenat
